0.title: Introduction

10.body: Packer is a plugin manager. It will download plugins from GitHub and add plugin into runtime path automatically. What it differ to other is that it can lazyload plugins easily. Here I will describe some usage and give some useful tips. For more details please read the packer.nvim README file: https://github.com/wbthomason/packer.nvim
10.title: Packer

11.body: The packer plugin is initialized in the lua/plugins.lua file. I called the require('packer').init in the beginning, and put two settings into it. The display setting set a floatting window with single line border for the packer panel. You can see the visual effect when you call any packer command. The git setting sets a timeout which will abort the update process when the git clone process is over 1 minute. And the require('packer').startup function at the end will handle all the plugins.
11.title: Basic

12.body: :PackerInstall: Run install process when you import new plugin. :PackerClean: Remove local plugins which is not in the plugin list. :PackerUpdate: Update all the plugin in the plugin list. :PackerSync: Run all the above command in one.
12.title: Commands

13.body:
If you want to add a plugin from GitHub, you can use the use function to add the plugin. For example, if you want to add the plugin trouble.nvim, and it's URL is https://github.com/folke/trouble.nvim, you only need to add the below snippet inside the require('packer').startup function: use { 'folke/trouble.nvim'
} After saving the file, run command :PackerInstall to install the plugin.
13.title: Add new plugin

14.body: You just need to delete the declaration line, then run :PackerClean.
14.title: Delete plugins

15.body: This is the key to make your neovim faster. fields value usage disable boolean Mark a plugin as inactive as string Specifies an alias under which to install the plugin installer function Specifies custom installer. See "custom installers" below. updater function Specifies custom updater. See "custom installers" below. after string or list Specifies plugins to load before this plugin. See "sequencing" below rtp string Specifies a subdirectory of the plugin to add to runtimepath. opt boolean Manually marks a plugin as optional. branch string Specifies a git branch to use tag string Specifies a git tag to use commit string Specifies a git commit to use lock boolean Skip updating this plugin in updates/syncs. Still cleans. run string, function, or table Post-update/install hook. See "update/install hooks". requires string or list Specifies plugin dependencies. Plugin in requires list can't be lazyload. rocks string or list Specifies Luarocks dependencies for the plugin config string or function Specifies code to run after this plugin is loaded.
15.title: Useful fields

16.body: fields value usage setup string or function pecifies code to run before this plugin is loaded. cmd string or list Specifies commands which load this plgin. Can be an autocmd pattern. ft string or list Specifies filetypes which load this plugin. key string or list Specifies maps which load this plugin. See "Keybindings". event string or list Specifies autocommand events which load this plugin. fn string or list Specifies functions which load this plugin. cond str/func/list of str/func Specifies a conditional test to load this plugin module string or list Specifies Lua module names for require. When requiring a string which starts with one of these module names, the plugin will be loaded. module_pattern string/list Specifies Lua pattern of Lua module names for require. When requiring a string which matches one of these patterns, the plugin will be loaded.
16.title: Lazyload settings

18.body:
Use the setup field. Example config: use { 'path/to/plugin', setup = function() -- this function will be called before the plugin loaded vim.g.settings = "your settings" end
}
18.breadcrumbs: Plugins » Packer » How to set up options before plugin load?
18.title: How to set up options before plugin load?

19.body:
Use the config field. Example config: use { 'plugin', config = function() require('plugin').setup{} end
}
19.breadcrumbs: Plugins » Packer » How to setup config after plugin load?
19.title: How to setup config after plugin load?

2.body: leader key is set to Space.
2.title: Leader key

20.body:
For example, the vim-fugitive provide command :Git, you can load the vim-fugitive command only when you call the Git command: use { 'tpope/vim-fugitive', cmd = { 'G', 'Git', 'Ggrep', 'Gdiffsplit', 'GBrowse' }
} With the above settings, vim-fugitive will not be sourced when you open the editor. It will only be sourced after you called the :G/:Git/:Ggrep/:Gdiffsplit/:GBrowse command.
20.breadcrumbs: Plugins » Packer » How to load plugin only when you called it's command
20.title: How to load plugin only when you called it's command

21.body:
In the below example, nvim-lsp-installer will only be loaded when you open file with .json, .py, and .js extension. use { 'williamboman/nvim-lsp-installer', ft = { "json", "python", "javascript" }, config = function() require("lspconfig") end
} Important notes : The ft field has more priviledge than the after field. So if you have ft and after for same plugin, it will first evaluate the filetype not the after field.
21.breadcrumbs: Plugins » Packer » How to load plugin only in specific filetype
21.title: How to load plugin only in specific filetype

22.body:
The telescope.nvim here will only be loaded after any code call the require("telescope"). use { 'nvim-telescope/telescope.nvim', requires = { 'nvim-lua/popup.nvim', 'nvim-lua/plenary.nvim' }, config = function() require("config.telescope_config") end, module = 'telescope'
}
22.breadcrumbs: Plugins » Packer » How to load plugin for specific module call
22.title: How to load plugin for specific module call
